At Lake Genava the Helvetii found their advance opposed by Caesar. Their most natural course was to cross the Rhene, pass- ing through a corner of the Roman province in southeastern Gaul. They sent a deputation asking permission to pass through the province without damage. To gain time, Caesar put them off to a second conference, spent the interval in constructinga line of fortifications along the Rhene, and then formally forbade their passage.

After vainly epdeavoring to force a'passage of the Rhone, the Helvetii, by arrangement with the Sequani, their neighbors on the northwest, proceeded to cross the Saone instead of the Rhene and thence to march westward. Caesar added five fresh legions to the one already athis disposal, and after about three-fourths of the Helvetian troops had crossed the Saone, fell upon and cut to pieres the remainder. Efferts on the part of the Helvetii to procure terms of peace satisfactory to themselves proved anavailÎ‡ ing, and after some minor contests the final decisive battle was fought at the Aeduan town, Bibracte, now Autun.
